metadata.name: codeTurning 1: Dotting #24
metadata.description:
The codeTurning project aims to reflect my journey from traditional tools to code, in which any day I learn a new skill.
Join me towards something new for me. Something different from the previous. 
Sometimes we will stand on the shoulders of giants.
 
Let's explore and see how far we get.
 
Lesson 1: Dotting
 
This is my first step.
The dotting series explores the technique of painting with dots-of-paint placed pseudo-randomly on the canvas.
 
------------
Thanks to Dario, Fernando, Alejandro, Piter, Diego, Manuel and Anthony for their support, especially for helping me to set up my project in the fxhash infrastructure.

metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #111
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Trading Art #8
metadata.description:
Visualize the price chart of major Forex pairs, BTC and ETH.

There are 5000 H1 candle data imported for each one, which means more than 50K H1 candles in total, with random background color, background patterns, and moving average period and style it provides good enough variations.

I start coding from first Covid quarantine by the Forex trading bots, first MQL4 then Python, and so on, in all of those experiences I have to play all the time with the OHLC data, which stands for Open, High, Low, and close price of a specific period, for example, one hour(H1).

Now I use them to make generative color paint for those people who are interested in Forex or Trading and spend a lot of time seeing these candles on the screen!

You can hold it in your wallet or print it and hang it on the wall.

Press “s” key to save in original size.

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Ceremony #217
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.
